[2] Guinea, diagnostics, funding

20 Apr 2016 Guinea: Last known Ebola patient discharged in Guinea
http://medicalxpress.com/news/2016-04-ebola-patient-discharged-guinea.html
[Guinea's health authorities and the medical charity treating the last known [Ebola virus disease (EVD)] patient in the country said Wed [20 Apr 2016] he had been discharged after successfully recovering from the disease.

The elderly man was shown smiling broadly in images released by the ALIMA medical charity, which treated him at their dedicated unit in the southern city of Nzerekore.

According to Fode Tass Sylla, spokesperson for Guinea's EVD response unit, "The last current confirmed case of Ebola hospitalized in Nzerekore left last night [Tue 19 April 2016] fully recovered, and has gone home."

"There are no more current confirmed cases in hospital and no suspected ones admitted to the center for the moment," the Alliance For International Medical Action (ALIMA) said in a statement.]

[This is at the same time that new cases have been observed in Liberia, presenting a new risk to Guinea. - Mod.LK]

and...

26 Apr 2016 Guinea: Ebola virus; Guinea authorities start count down to end Ebola in Guinea
http://www.albanydailystar.com/health/after-2-years-finally-end-of-ebola-in-guinea-bellevue-tech-time-10627.html
[Authorities have started the countdown to the end of Ebola in Guinea, the last country still reporting cases after nearly 2 years. The patient's recovery and the lack of new cases raise hopes that Guinea -- and the world -- could end Ebola transmission before the end of the year [2016]. Guinea must still go 42 days without any new cases and after that must maintain a period of heightened surveillance.

Health officials performed a 2nd test Mon [27 Apr 2016] on a baby whose mother had died in October [2015] from Ebola. "The baby is negative, and so Guinea today [26 Apr 2016] is without a single Ebola patient," said Fode Tass Sylla, spokesman for Guinea's national Ebola response taskforce. "We are crossing our fingers and praying that nothing will happen over the next 42 days so that we can celebrate Guinea without Ebola."

The World Health Organization declares that Ebola disease transmission has ended when the country goes through 2 incubation periods -- 21 days each -- without a new case emerging. The other 2 countries hardest hit by the virus -- Sierra Leone and Liberia -- already have reached that benchmark. But authorities in Guinea said they continued to face resistance in fearful communities, where people initially blamed international health workers for bringing the virus to their region. Many preferred to bring their sick to traditional healers instead of Ebola clinics and often buried the dead without conforming to the health rules that were designed to prevent mourners from being infected by corpses.

A baby girl in Guinea, who was the last known Ebola patient in a 2-year regional epidemic, has recovered from the disease but remained under surveillance at a medical facility in the capital Conakry on Tuesday [26 Apr 2016], health officials said. The baby's recovery means that Guinea, the last country still battling the virus, can begin its 42-day countdown to declaring an end to outbreak.

In a major breakthrough, neighboring Sierra Leone was declared Ebola-free on 7 Nov [2015]. "We did 2 tests that turned up negative. She is completely cured of Ebola," said Fodé Tass Sylla, spokesman for Guinea's Ebola coordination unit. The baby was born on 27 Oct [2015] in the Nongo Ebola treatment center to an infected mother who did not survive. Nubia received treatment from medical charity Medecins Sans Frontieres (MSF).

"We are pleased that she has been tested negative, but as she is the 1st infected baby to have recovered, she will continue to receive specialized medical support before going back home," said Laurence Sailly, MSF's emergency coordinator in Guinea.

68 people who had been in contact with the country's last cluster of patients and were deemed at risk of developing the hemorrhagic fever were released from quarantine on Sat [24 Apr 2016].

The epidemic, the worst known Ebola outbreak in history, began in Guinea's forest region nearly 2 years ago and has since killed around 11 300 people, nearly all of them in West African neighbors Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone. ...more]

[Ebola has been particularly hard on mothers and babies. This is great news that a baby has recovered. - Mod.LK]

27 Apr 2016 USA: Center for Strategic and International Studies releases U.S. Ebola response documentary
https://homelandprepnews.com/countermeasures/18695-center-strategic-international-studies-releases-u-s-ebola-response-documentary/
[The Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) released a feature-length documentary on Fri [22 Apr 2016] entitled "Ebola in America: Epidemic of Fear," based on the timeline of the [Ebola virus disease (EVD)] crisis and how the United States responded to it.

The documentary contains interviews from those most intimately involved in the crisis, including missionary Dr. Kent Brantly, the 1st American to return to the U.S. for treatment of EVD. The documentary also focuses on the efforts the U.S. took to respond EVD, with additional insight from interviews with White House Ebola Czar Ron Klain, CDC Director Tom Frieden and other prominent 1st responders who became involved in countering the outbreak.

According to Dr. J. Stephen Morrison, senior vice president and director of CSIS's Global Health Policy Center and leader of the project, "When Ebola arrived in America in 2014, it ignited the best and the worst in us, including fear, panic, stigma, confrontation, and confusion, and courage and leadership. We've tried to unpack this turbulence through the eyes of different key individuals on the front lines. Their story resonates today as we face Zika and the threat of infants born with brain damage."]

Diagnostics
-------
22 Apr 2016: Authorization of emergency use of an in vitro diagnostic device for detection of Ebola Zaire virus; availability
https://www.federalregister.gov/articles/2016/04/22/2016-09369/authorization-of-emergency-use-of-an-in-vitro-diagnostic-device-for-detection-of-ebola-zaire-virus
[The Food and Drug Administration (FDA) is announcing the issuance of an Emergency Use Authorization (EUA) (the Authorization) for an in-vitro diagnostic device for detection of the Ebola Zaire virus in response to the Ebola virus outbreak in West Africa. The FDA issued this Authorization under the Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act (the FD&C Act), as requested by OraSure Technologies, Inc. The Authorization contains, among other things, conditions on the emergency use of the authorized in vitro diagnostic device. (See the Authorization, which includes an explanation of the reasons for issuance, reprinted in this article.)]

Vaccine
----
25 Apr 2016: NewLink Genetics Awarded USD 21.6 Million Contract Option by BARDA for Ebola Vaccine Development
http://globenewswire.com/news-release/2016/04/25/832157/0/en/NewLink-Genetics-Awarded-21-6-Million-Contract-Option-by-BARDA-for-Ebola-Vaccine-Development.html
[Biopharmaceutical company NewLink Genetics Corporation announced today [25 Apr 2016] that the Biomedical Advanced Research and Development Authority (BARDA) of the United States Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) has exercised its USD 21.6 million option to support continued development of the investigational rVSV-ZEBOV-GP (Ebola) vaccine candidate. The funds will be used to conduct clinical bridging studies to further assess the vaccine's safety, immunogenicity and efficacy in populations different from the original testing region.]

Funding
------
27 Apr 2016 USA: Senator introduces legislation to fight diseases such as Zika and Ebola: Al Franken of Minnesota aims to establish a coordinated One Health response to animal disease outbreaks.
http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/senator-introduces-legislation-fight-diseases-such-zika-and-ebola
[US Senator Al Franken (Dem-MN) endeavors to establish a coordinated One Health response to zoonotic disease outbreaks. The One Health Act of 2016 would task the nation's regulatory agencies, including the Centers for Disease Control, Department of Homeland Security and the U.S. Department of Agriculture, to work together to understand, prevent and respond to zoonotic disease outbreaks. If passed, the One Health Act of 2016 would also create competitive grant programs to carry out the programs outlined in the framework and stimulate collaboration between health programs at the state and local level. The legislation also urges international health organizations to increase investments in One Health approaches to global health security.]
[Terrific approach, important to global public health. - Mod.LK]

Research
-----
23 Apr 2016: Neurologic problems common in Ebola survivors
http://www.medpagetoday.com/MeetingCoverage/AAN/57503
[According to Lauren Bowen, MD, a National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke clinical fellow, speaking at the American Academy of Neurology annual meeting, nearly all Liberian [Ebola virus disease (EVD)] survivors examined in a study conducted by National Institutes of Health researchers reported neurological symptoms, persisting in many cases for more than a year.

About 75 percent of the 164 survivors studied as of February 2016 reported experiencing headaches during or after stays in Ebola treatment units, and 50 percent reported difficulty walking and overall muscle weakness, Moreover, headache, depression, and memory loss continued in 50 percent or more when interviewed a year or more after treatment unit discharge.

Dr Bowen said one of the most surprising findings was the frequency of hallucinations, some of which were very concerning. Bowen mentioned 10-year-olds having hallucinations severe enough to require psychiatric hospitalization.

Almost 25 percent of the sample reported having hallucinations during or after their treatment unit stays. These tended not to be persistent, with only 4 percent reporting such symptoms at follow-up. However, Dr. Bowen said this is still far above the level expected in the general Liberian population.

Sexual dysfunction was noted in 29 percent of subjects, with most of the sexual problems of the under-functioning type, but hypersexuality was reported by some participants.

Less common symptoms included tremor, abnormal thoughts and behaviors, and incontinence.]

[As is often the case with virus infection, the acute symptoms are sometimes only one aspect of the disease. The sequelae are also a serious health problem. - Mod.LK]

